Simply awesome, a new thing... great! A must see
One of the best movies in recent memory, Moonlight perfectly captures a relevant topic about African American gay youth and the discrimination they face, and how it shapes their lives, with an amazing story, making the viewer become emotionally attached to Chiron. Barry Jenkins shows his brilliance as a director with ana amazing screenplay, but what stands out is the amazing cinematography and the way many scenes are beautifully shot, but also hold a deeper meaning tied into both the social commentary but also the aspect of the characters psychological state. It is truly fascinating. The acting is flawless. This is one of the greatest acted movies I have ever seen. All Chiron Performances are amazing.  Alex.R Hibbert has an amazing, powerful performance at a young age, showing that he is destined for greatness. Ashton Sanders captures teenage Chiron, someone who is beginning to find out who he is but has to deal with homophobia and a troubled household perfectly. Trevante Rhodes perfectly shows an Older Chron, someone who is trying to hide his identity and gives one of the best performances in the entire film. Naomie Harris is outstanding as Paula, Chiron's mother, who struggles with addiction, and has a love for her son but values her need to self medicate more than anything. Mahershala Ali wins a well deserved Oscar for his performance as Juan, who in just over 30 minutes of screentime, gave what might be the best performance in the film. Despite being a dealer, he proves to be an important figure in shaping Chiron, but it also leaves the viewer with a conflict, as they know Chiron's mother is a bad influence, but to escape it he meets Juan, who also seen later in the film, led Chiron in his same footsteps as a dealer, or one can say it is fate, just one of the many psychological questions this film asks. This is one of the best supporting performances of the last decade. Jharrel Jerrome is great as teen Kevin, and Andre Holland is great as older Kevin. The side characters from the bullies, to the teachers, to the counselors are all amazing as well. If anybody wants to see amazing acting, beautiful cinematography, in a brilliantly written film about an extremely relevant social topic, this is the film to see.
