Expands the stories of LGBTQ stories in america. Really cool, passionate, intimate storytelling.
As a guy who didn't like Boyhood, I feel like Moonlight, another film about a boy growing up, was infinitely better.

Boyhood explored every single detail about Mason's life, and many of those details don't translate well as a narrative. Many plot points would be quickly forgotten and were never referenced again.

Moonlight only shows three parts of Chiron's life, but those three parts are the most vital to the plot. This creates a narrative that is very engaging.

Another thing I didn't like about Boyhood was that it shoved in a bunch of pop-culture references that were really dated by the time the film hit theaters.

Moonlight never quite specifies when it takes place, making the film feel more timeless as the years go by.


I know a lot of people really loved Boyhood, but I personally think Moonlight was a much better film on just about every level. The characters are more interesting, the story is very interesting, the editing is beyond genius, and overall, I feel that Moonlight will hold up in the years to come.
This is one of the more interesting Best Picture winners that I have ever seen, it's a story about underprivileged African-Americans that is not seen through a white lens. There is no black and white in this film, those who treat the main character with love and care are complicit in the abuse of others and that makes a very complex film. Having recently seen If Beale Street Could Talk (2018) it was rewarding to look back at Barry Jenkins' breakout film and see all of the flourishes that make him such a unique director. Thank goodness that this and not the cringe worthy and forgettable La La Land (2016).

We see a man Chiron,, at three different stages in his life as he progresses from troubled child with an abusive mother to confused homosexual teenager to emotionally neutered adult. The figures surrounding him who most matter are his drug-addicted mother, Naomie Harris, his childhood mentor, Mahershala Ali, and his high school friend,,. His mentor tries to teach him how to live a moral life but Chiron ends up following in his footsteps and becoming a drug dealer himself whilst his friend gives him a hand job on the beach but later beats him up after facing peer pressure. All of the abuse he has faced in his life lead to him becoming a man who directs all of his energy into exercise and the illegal activities that help him earn a living whilst having no outlet for his sexual frustration.

What makes the film special is that these people are seen as just that normal people, not slaves or slightly simple but innocent folks who need to be helped along by an intellectually superior white person. Chiron faces many difficulties in his life a lot of which are probably influenced by racial inequality in the United States but racism is not the focus of the story instead we see his troubled coming of age in a black community in which complex figures exist. Teresa, Janelle Monae, is a kind, motherly figure that Chiron can look up to instead of his own abusive, troubled mother. We see two very different women, both black, with major supporting roles who both have significant flaws whilst also having redemptive moments. This sort of nuance is not present in The Help (2011) or The Blind Side (2009) in which African-Americans are reduced to supporting players who need the help of Emma Stone or Sandra Bullock.

The presence of an extremely quiet, self-contained lead character could have made the film difficult to engage with but fortunately all three actors who portrayed the main character were very good at conveying internal strife. In particular,, was able to capture his character's ambivalence about his sexual attraction to his best friend. The actors manage to make their version of the character feel like a natural progression instead of feeling like a completely different interpretation this means that emotional moments have more impact as we have sympathy for that little boy on the beach when we understand that Chiron has become as bad as his mentor.

If I had any criticism of the film, I have very little, I would say it's a fairly ugly film and I understand that the location that Chiron lives in is either rough or just dull but I still believe that more effort could be put in to add something to visual style of this film. In Knight of Cups (2015), a very different film I know, Christian Bale or Rick, as his character is known, visits Skid Row one of the roughest neighborhoods in the United States and yet through the lens of Emmanuel Lubezki there is a strange beauty to it. Lubezki is one of the best cinematographers working today and not every film is going to look as beautiful as something directed by Terrence Malick but you would still hope for something approaching grotesque beauty.

This was definitely a deserving Best Picture winner as it was much better than any of the other films nominated that year but I personally preferred Manchester by the Sea (2016). Kudos to the Academy for rewarding a non-white savior narrative film about people of color, it's about damn time, but it's rather disappointing to see them regress with Green Book (2018).
I know why it is relevant, I know why it is praised, and I know it is not my kinda movie.
boyhood: who are you?
moonlight: i'm you but stronger in every possible way
I  thought this would be a rough film to get through. Turns out it ended up being one of my favorites of the year. So simple and so complex at the same time.
I've seen Moonlight four times and I feel that this is the best film of all time. Never has anything I've ever seen come close to Moonlight, Barry Jenkins is going to achieve legendary status as a director in the near future as he wrings beauty in every scene despite the bleakest of circumstances. The three act structure is beautiful as we see a vulnerable boy who can't be himself struggle to find himself in his bleak life in working class America. It's a film unlike any other and one of the most deserved best picture winners ever. This will and always will be my favourite film and I have a feeling I'm going to enjoy every single film Jenkins makes.
