Best Picture Oscar Winner 2017 Review
**3.5 Stars**
Considering I could have written this review back in September, 2016 (after seeing Moonlight at TIFF) I kept putting it off until I started writing it in November.  Hadn't fully completed it, and in thinking I had saved it as draft, I soon found out that I had not.  Was it a harbinger or an omen to postpone it for a later time?  Especially with that Oscar mess-up fiasco which occurred at the end of this year's Oscar's telecast?  Possibly.  Where we left our friend's Oscar party right after La La Land was called Best Picture.  8 mins later I get a text saying they messed up: Moonlight was the actual winner.  I was like "you're PUNKING me?!"  Alas, it turned out he was not: Moonlight was the true Best Picture winner.
Did it deserve it?  *shrugs*.  It wasn't my top pick.  Same for La La Land: meh & not my top pick.  Arrival would have been my Best Picture pick.  Not to say Moonlight wasn't deserving of the kudos and praise, cause it was.  Especially for the acting by Alex R Hibbert as the first third of the movie's young "Little; by Ashton Sanders as the middle third's Chiron; and by Mahershala Ali (Best Supporting Actor winner) as the father figure to Little, Juan.  Trevante Rhodes (tv actor from Westworld), as the final third's Black, was also quite captivating, having to act through gold grill teeth with a complete lack of emotion and speech (compared to the verbose Little).  
As a gay guy, I didn't feel Moonlight was a "gay" movie.  To me, it was more of a movie surrounding the exploration and determination of someone's sexuality.  A lot of critics, reviews and hype has been made surrounding Moonlight being a "gay" movie or about gay sexuality.  Which - to me - wasn't the correct framing point or stance.  We all develop our sexual interests through different avenues, pathways and choices in life.  The events in the middle third of the movie - focusing on Chiron - mitigates the confrontation of sexuality in the Black's final third.  Moonlight is, more so, the impact and mental and psychological tug of war someone goes through to truly try to find out who they are and how they identify themselves.  Which - at the end of Moonlight - is still left up in the air.  A perfect way to end it by NOT making it a gay movie.
Because of how it was presented, I give total props to (Best) director and writer Barry Jenkins for his intimate, questioning, non-linear, non-surrender to gay clich√© character drama.  Jenkins' direction showcases both the gritty, destitute, drug-run landscapes of Miami, Florida as well as the almost angelic, soul-saving moments of life, such as when Ali's Juan teaches Little to swim.  
At the same time, I also wasn't blown away by Moonlight because of its segmented, non-linear sequencing.  Jenkins shows us parts - the most impactful parts - of a character's sexual trajectory.  However, there is a lot is left out and not captured; moments of Little/Chiron/Black's growing up that is left in the cracks and spaces in between the specifically pinpointed chapters we are shown.  As such, Moonlight doesn't feel smoothly cohesive overall.  Possibly a minor gripe, but one that didn't make me jump up and down when it was correctively announced as Best Picture.
Also, I found Naomi Harris' (who I LOVED in 28 Days Later and Skyfall) portrayal of Little/Chiron/Black's mother Paula clich√©d, "seen it done better," and not hard hitting enough (a la Monique in Precious).
And Janelle Monae (also seen in this year's Best Picture Nominated Hidden Figures) was a little too pretty and polished looking in her role as Teresa, Juan's girlfriend/partner.  
Again, maybe minor nitpickings, but ones that made it a good movie but not a perfect movie.
Just saw Moonlight yesterday.  Great acting, but have no idea how it won Best Picture over fantastic movies like Hidden Figures, Lion and Hacksaw Ridge.
A combination of brutal & beautiful.
the plight of a gay boy becoming a man in one of the roughest places in Miami made for a phenomenal movie. The direction they decided to take the movie was the perfect artistic choice; one that I thought they weren't going to take, but I was pleasantly surprised with part 3 goin the direction it did.
very interesting. new perspective for sure.
Let's first admit that there is a major drift in the contemporary film industry between what good filmmaking is and what content might be, the global scene is confused as to what really makes a good movie, and momentary social, cultural and political influences make this confusion far worse, and it's because of this that a movie like Moonlight ever received any recognition in the first place.

Technically, the film's reality is that it's completely amateurish, if I didn't know better I'd have thought it was a film school project at best, a screenplay that wants to say things but doesn't, a director who shoots whatever is available and moves to the next shot, and a horrible editing job that would be so bad even for a first draft it makes you lose any sense of pacing or story.

Basically it's a movie with a very specific audience that might appreciate it, and unfortunately, the people working on the Academy Awards are part of that demographic, but the movie will always fail to be universal, not because of its setting or its character, people loved City of God and it was celebrated worldwide, while Moonlight will never be because of all of its mediocre elements that hinder it from being relatable, unless you're an American justice warrior who wants to capture the bold lines of a story about a poor gay black kid growing up as a headline with total disregard to what the movie really is.

In 20 years, we'll look back and wonder how was it even possible for this mediocre piece to get half the recognition it received, because the momentary circumstances that lead to its acceptance would have changed, and that is not what cinema is about, cinema is meant to be universal and eternal, even if humanity as we know it has completely changed.
This movie doesn't deserve that high rating
