Ultimately a film that doesn't really fit any of the labels you might expect going into it and I came out of it not much wiser. The crime element is always there but never a focus and it's not an obvious romance either. So much of the story happens off-screen but in a way that works. Chiron's first 3 decades are covered in snapshots and by the character's nature he's very closed off with only occasional moments of emotion escaping out. The supporting cast is where most of the emotion comes from and lucklily the entire cast is very strong. I was also impressed with how they managed to maintain the chemistry between the 3 versions of Kevin and Chiron. The only real shame is that Mahershala Ali doesn't get a much bigger part as the conflicted drug dealer who takes Chiron under his wing as the character was complex and Ali made any scene with him in shine. I'm often a bit lazy and prefer not to fill in the gaps so much with a film but this one just gets away with it.
Mahershala's role is important, if brief, and set's a quietly poignant tone in the first act.  All three incarnations of our protagonist are well executed and consistent.  And the message of this film is a lot more powerful than the mere narrative of Chiron's life.
