Beautifully shot and emotionally raw, Moonlight tells a story that is as sensitive to our modern landscape as it a timeless social commentary. It is a story, told in three parts, about a young, black man growing up in the midst of confusion (of the pain of life, his sexuality, and the meaning of love).  

In terms of the theme of the young man's struggle with sexuality, it is told with surprising constraint, with greater attention given to his relationship to the world around him (and his inner struggles playing into that). In terms of the sheer pain that he carries, the film allows that to slowly unravel through the use of colour, textures, tone, silence and the odd emotional burst. 

I found Moonlight to be much more blatant in its hopeful nature than the much more nuanced undercurrents of Manchester By the Sea, even if the two are similar types of films that really dig underneath of the surface of some incredibly tough themes. This is what allows, for example, the mother in the third act to make such an immediate turn around from the dire place we last see her. Without the films positive outlook, I think our ability to see her character as anything other than vile and unforgivable would be greatly challenged, but as it is, the affect of the film in allowing us to see the characters as more than just the brokenness and the hurt arrives by slowly encouraging our ability to forgive as we watch the films main character seem to forgive the impossible in his own life. 

I will admit, I wasn't overwhelmed by this film, at least not in the same way as Manchester. It took me a bit to get over the fact that they play three different actors for the same character who look nothing alike. And there are points where I felt the dramatic scenes were slightly overplayed for the affect of what becomes a rather frustrating and persisting silence (of someone who has been left with very few words). But it would take a hard heart indeed not to be won over by the films honesty. And thematically, the film really does work as a multi-faced commentary on what it means to find yourself alone, to face rejection in home and at school, and to struggle with the expectations and stereotypes of masculinity.
