7.6/10, my review: http://wp.me/p1eXom-2PA
A moving tale of a black gay boy growing up in a world were vulnerability is punished. A story which celebrates love and masculinity with as much beauty as it's musical scores... Barry Jenkins writes and directes this uplifting tale which, if it wins the best film at the Oscars, is surely not gonna be a surprise.
A strong storyline with clear message which is engaging throughout. The camera work and use of sound was fascinating. The first 2 acts were great but for me the third act lacked impact.
Essentially we follow Chiron, a black kid growing up in Miami through three chapters - childhood, as a teenager and as an adult, intertwined with his childhood friend Kevin. Throughout his mother is played by Naomie Harris. In the first chapter "Little" (a delightful performance by Alex Hibbert) is picked upon as he is small and shy, he is taken tenderly under the fatherly wing of local crack dealer Juan (Mahershala Ali), who co-incidentally supplies his mother with her drugs. In the second chapter Chiron is at high school, where the bullying continues. He is drawn back to his childhood friend Kevin (who now calls him "Black" and they have their first sexual encounter - however school play ground posturing leads to them both being drawn into an ugly fight. In the last chapter, we have moved to Atlanta "Black", has undergone an improbable transformation into thick muscle-set hunk (Trevante Rhodes), who now deals crack himself - with many echoes of his childhood father figure/mentor, just with bigger bling. After not seeing each other for many years, Kevin calls Chiron and they meet as adults and reconcile. Acting is superb throughout, with themes explored in a personal, rather than in your face way. Mood and tone are set perfectly with an excellent soundtrack, alongside some very strong visual segments.
