The elements in Moonlight, race, drugs, violence, homophobia, poverty are ones that most gay men are familiar with, as are people of color. Having been through some of these circumstances myself, I can tell you that much of the movie rings true. The drugs, the poverty, the homophobia, the violence are all things I've lived myself, and this movie doesn't sugarcoat them, nor does it condemn them. They just ARE. 
The only thing I wanted, as a viewer, was more time spent on the end. But it wasn't needed, and would have only been there to satisfy the needs of the more romantic viewers. The three actors that played Chiron through the three stages of his life were all very good. They got enough of his quiet manner, his hesitancy to speak, into all 3 portrayals that it felt authentic, like I was seeing the same boy/teen/man throughout. I recommend this movie if you like gritty dramas with some heart.
Boys In The Hood meets Brokeback Mountain!
Moonlight presents three vignettes of a young black man struggling with his sexuality in a poor neighborhood in the Deep South. Each snapshot takes place in a different period in this guy's life and he's portrayed by a different actor in each instance. Writer/director Barry Jenkins handles this film with a skill and delicacy that splits the difference between the roving cinematography of Akira Kurosawa and the unorthodox emotive arrangements of David Lynch. The result is a moving and immaculately-designed character drama that takes full advantage of compelling performances from Naomie Harris, Mahershala Ali, Trevante Rhodes, Ashton Sanders, and the rest of the superb cast.
It's a beautiful movie, both visually and in terms of its storytelling.  The drama is understated yet intimate, and it will leave you feeling a full range of emotions.

