Groundbreaking perfection!
A gripping tale about sensitive subjects that is a welcome addition to cinema. 

The tender, heartbreaking story of a young man's struggle to find himself, told across three defining chapters in his life as he experiences the ecstasy, pain, and beauty of falling in love, while grappling with his own sexuality.

I knew relatively nothing about this film going into it. I knew nothing about the plot, nothing about the subject, and saw no trailers. In all honesty, that lack of knowledge had my interest at a low. However, upon viewing this film, I instantly found out why it was nominated for multiple awards.

The story of this film is amazing. It's a gripping tale with three phases, one phase for each major portion of this boy's life. Each period shows the hardships he experiences as he grows up and takes us along that journey with him. The emotional and physical stress he experiences are so draining that you see just how it affects him as he grows older. The story is very unique in the sense that not many films out there showcase this subject as their main plot, but this film paid major respects to a subject of this level.

The acting was flat out amazing. Each actor, starting with the kid all the way to the adult, were all fantastic. I felt like I was watching the same exact boy grow up with the same personality. It felt like one character and one man, which shows just how well they kept the continuity between actors. They were all amazing in their own way and they each brought something unique to the table. They did a fantastic job of bringing out the story and its message.

The cinematography wasn't my absolute favorite, but I still appreciate it and I recognize what they were going for. I personally didn't think it was perfect, however, it was still above average. The shots overall looked good and the way the film was edited was solid. There were many cases where there were nice, smooth one-takes, and other instances where the camera movement brought out the intensity of the scene.

In the end, "Moonlight" also would've made my top 10 list of the year had I seen it prior. It's an amazing film with a fantastic story that I think many people should watch.
