Moonlight is based off the acclaimed play 'In Moonlight Black Boys Look Blue'. The play and movie tells the story of Chiron, a young gay black boy living in a hostile area with a drug addicted mother and the way the environment shapes his beliefs and him as a person. Moonlight is a phenomenal film that tells a brilliant and heartbreaking story of nature vs nurture. This is a power house of a movie with so many positives to talk about which is amazing. For one the acting is amazing. Chiron's story is told over threee periods in his life, as a child, as a teenager and as an adult. Therefore three actors have to play Chiron and luckily they are all fantastic. Alex Hibbert, Ashton Sanders and Trevante Rhodes are all fantastic and all bring so much to this character. Chiron is a brilliant character and these three actors are able to add so much both obvious and subtle to this character that makes each version similar yet unique. The film also has some truly exceptional supporting acting. Naomie Harris plays Chiron's mother and she is exceptional. Her character is a lot of the times very easy to hate and also can be quite likeable. Harris gives her best performance ever here as she adds so much to the character and is truly deserving of all recognition she is getting here. Mahershala Ali of Luke Cage and House of Cards fame also stars and he in my opinion gives the best performance of the film. True his character may not be in the film a lot but Ali gives an exceptional turn here as he's both extremely likeable and also immoral and complex which makes his character one of the best of the film. I absolutely loved his final moment as it was so sudden yet so amazing. Janelle Mon√°e stars as Ali's girlfriend and she is really great and extremely likeable. The three actors who also play Chiron's best friend Kevin are also fantastic. Just like the three who play Chiron, Jayden Piner, Jharrel Jerome and Andr√© Holland are all fantastic and add a lot to this character. The acting is fantastic and carries the movie but it would be criminal to not mention the direction. Barry Jenkins does a superb job at directing. This movie is very gritty and depressing but also has a really unique and beautiful dream like feel. Jenkins does a superb job at telling this story and in my opinion this is some of the best directing I've seen in a while. Technically this film is absolutely top notch. The cinematography by James Laxton is amazing! The film looks unbelievably fantastic. You honestly could just pause this film at any moment and just sit there and admire the fantastic colours and angles. The editing by both Joi McMillon and Nat Sanders is brilliant. This movie flows so well and a lot of the cuts are really excellent which is something I can't say for a lot of movies. The film is very well paced and luckily is never boring. The music I also found really fantastic. Nicholas Britell's score is truly excellent and I loved how it gets reused a lot in the film but with variations that appropriately fit with the film. One of the things I was worried about with Moonlight is that because it's broken up into segments there would be a really weak section, however each segment of Chiron's life just builds and builds and it's one of those movies that gets better as it goes along. Moonlight is definitely not a film for all however as there are a lot of scenes that can be quite difficult to watch and at times this movie is a real downer. However I believe everyone should see Moonlight as in my opinion this is an incredibly important film. It tells an important and powerful story and isn't afraid to shy away from anything. It's Moonlight's ending that truly proves how great of a film this is as it's both a happy ending and a soul crushingly depressing one. The whole third act is very complex and powerful just through seeing how the characters have evolved. This movie isn't incredibly rewatchable due to the intense and depressing story telling but it's a film you will not be able to stop thinking about. As for flaws I only have one. At times I unfortunately did find it a bit difficult to hear some of the characters bit even then it's such a minor and infrequent flaw and doesn't really detract from the overall quality. Moonlight is a very adult and mature film about race, prejudice and most importantly love. I absolutely adored Moonlight, it's so powerful and impactful and I have not been able to stop thinking about it since I stopped watching. A truly exceptional film that while not a fun watch is an extremely important one. See this movie now, it's an absolute masterpiece of cinema. A+
I could not connect emotionally with the story; in spite of this, though, I really appreciated the way the script and dialogue were devised. In that way, the viewers are given a great window into how the main character's [Chiron's] life is shaped by each moment. I also liked the pacing and how the story was set up in different sections, done in a similar way to other "coming-of-age" movies (such as 2014's "Boyhood," as others have pointed out) but in a more-incredible fashion. To be honest, each performance from the members of the wonderful cast is so fantastic that I have a hard time singling anyone out (with maybe Trevante Rhodes and Andre Holland as the exceptions); acting nominations for awards consideration are well-deserved all around. In addition, the music accompanying the flick was also touching in its own way, as it haunts the viewer throughout the narrative. This film holds a place as one of my favorite films of the past year, and I am really glad I was able to see it.
A beautifully deep, authentic movie. Gorgeous film, expertly acted. Provoking. Mahershala Ali is a superb actor -- and this is some of his most honest work. Which is saying something.
By far the best movie of 2016
Driven to watch this movie by its powerful trailer, exalting it as 'the reason we go to the movies', i was very intrigued. However, for me the film never delivers on the promise of its first act. I understand that the wider themes that the film is trying to portray but exposition is not always a bad thing when utilized correctly.  The film is intentionally opaque to the point it becomes slow. By the conclusion, the silence of Chiron becomes more frustrating than anything, which is a metaphor for the film as a whole; if you have something to say, say it!
Visually, Moonlight is a masterpiece, and its cast shine as bright, but in terms of storytelling, it is not that compelling.
I thought it was about one thing and it turned out to be about something else unexpected
not my cup of tea.. wasted of money
Hauntingly beautiful and simplistic.  The acting is so stellar and raw that I felt as if I were watching actual people rather than actors. The movie does not try unnecessarily hard to make the audience emotional: the story and acting stands for itself. The soundtrack, on an additional note, was wonderful--it really added to the overall sense of drama and devastation. Really beautiful and thoughtful movie that causes you to think, although for some it may seem "slow" at times, understandably, but I interpret these lulls as the film striving to be more realistic and thoughtful. Loved it!
Reel Dialogue: Moonlight review

Being awards season, this little film has gained world-wide acclaim.

