The other day I watched Moonlight and I wanted to take a couple more days to digest it and gather my thoughts on it. Moonlight is a stellar film. It tells the story of a young man who struggles through isolation, race and sexuality through 3 different times of his life. It is very good at having raw emotion from all the characters. Mahershala Ali is well deserving of his supporting actor nomination. For me personally though, I am not sure if I will ever watch Moonlight again. Its one of those films you absolutely have to see but not sure if you'll ever watch it again. It's not my cup of tea but I am still glad I watched it. It was great, but rewatchability is low for me.
Oh what a difference a few weeks make. The movie has pacing and some thematic flaws, but when framed in the perspective of masculinity in general and Black masculinity in particular, the story and characters must be viewed differently. The story isn't about Chiron's love so much as it is his ability to love. It must be understood, however, that the vehicle for this story is chock full of pretentious Oscar-Bait tropes that are designed to get viewers feeling like they're watching something important. But that doesn't change that Moonlight IS an important movie. 

