I'm not black and I'm not gay, but the struggle for identity in your teens is all to familiar to me. As I too was beaten up a lot at school for being to soft and too feminine, the middle part of the movie really got to me. The big difference off course is that being black means the repercussions of fighting back against your oppressors, your upbringing, and your neighborhood is very different from my white, privileged youth. I found Moonlight to be a touching, if slightly distant story with three brilliant actors inhabiting one character in three different times of his life.
