"Moonlight," an Oscar Best Picture nominee, takes an unconventional approach to telling the story of a young African-American, Chiron, growing up poor and gay in an extremely tough environment in inner-city Miami. Three different actors portray Chiron from about age nine to full adulthood. It reminded me a lot of "Lion," another Best-Picture candidate, because both portray kids forced to almost raise themselves and both movies highlight settings (Miami's Liberty City and Calcutta, India) that are completely alien to me. The acting is great, including Mahershala Ali (as a drug dealer) and Janelle Monae (of "Hidden Figures") as the most positive role models for a kid who is terrorized at school and at home. There's enough visual flair in the story-telling for me to recommend seeing this on a big screen. I really liked it. 8/10.
