It's wonderful that this movie exists, tragic that so much of it feels to real, and miraculous that it's being so widely seen and lauded. Rhodes and Holland generate twenty times the on screen heat as Ledger and Gyllenhaal did, and Sanders is phenomenal as the lynchpin between past and future. It's an emotional, deeply felt, gingerly observed meditation I still can't believe has seen the light of day. We may live in Trump's America, but we live in this moonlit one too.
