Such delicate subjects, so complex and so real, however, so little discussed. "Moonlight" is a very elaborated introspection of the human mind, in this case we're talking about the mind of a boy named Chiron, who lives with his mother in a neighborhood mostly of African-American population in the city of Miami, Florida. The film is carefully divided into three episodes: the first one shows the little Chiron, who constantly suffers from school harassment by his classmates, and is picked up by Juan (Mahershala Ali) who receives him from there countless times due to the problems the boy has at home with his drug-addicted mother and all the problems at school. The second chapter shows the adolescent Chiron (Ashton Sanders) and the third to the adult, (Trevante Rhodes) who suffers from significant changes in his image and his lifestyle. Every detail of the film was carefully done and completed and Barry Jenkins and guarantees that although he uses different actors in each chapter, they retain every characteristic that identifies the central figure of Chiron. The glance that these actors reflect is incredibly similar, being captivating and hopeful, and this film recounts the pilgrimage of Chiron in his search of identity and in the quest to take a place in society.
The face that shows us from the United States, especially from Miami has been little explored, we know that there are very large migrant populations in this city, but filmmakers rarely immerse themselves so thoroughly in this environment. The situations that happen are so real and vivid that we can often wonder if that kind of things can really happen there, and it really is like that. Drugs, homosexuality, identity, masculinity, race, culture and society are themes that explicitly or implicitly are handled in this extraordinary history and Jenkins constitutes a plot that can touch the most sensitive fibers of the audience, showing few dialogues but natural and very intimate actions which make us understand the difficulties that people under tough environments have to deal with. From the beginning, Chiron is shy, unable to make friends, he is black and gay, so the environment in which he grows is very much against him. Jenkins expatiates to be tolerant, understanding and determined, so "Moonlight" is nothing more than a remarkable film that should be seen and enjoyed by anyone in any context, because this it is a movie for everyone. Moonlight inevitably generates a cinematographic work that provides a new experience, as it is neither spectacular nor with great effects, but it is provides a new full perspective. Chiron as a person was efficiently completed, his performance was wonderful, I stated that adult Chiron had many changes but at the end he deeply shows that he is exactly the same on his inside, so we don't have a doubt that the work of Jenkins as a director in this movie was fascinating. It is one of the most entrancing films of 2016 and is positioned very close to perfection, the language of silence that is used here is impeccable and the teachings that are conveyed are unforgettable. I loved the fact that it was not this big tragedy like many movies of similar themes are, because over time things improved here and everything was well-connected so that the main character would settle more in the place that he belonged: to love and to be loved. 94/100
Beautiful film. Don't think I've seen anything like this before. There's a kind of art¬óor maybe, more precisely¬óa kind of experience with art, that exposes you to emotions or realities that you didn't know existed. Perhaps there are other films out there that have previously documented this experience, that of growing up gay and black in the inner city, where being gay is seen as "softness" and softness makes you prey for those who need to show how hard they are. Perhaps this is a story that's been told before and I just haven't come across it. But this story comes with an urgency to be told. It feels like a story that refuses not to be heard any longer. This struggle to exist and be heard is the struggle not just of the story but of the characters themselves. The protagonist¬ówho has a new name in each act and has outgrown it by the end of that act¬óis visibly and painfully unable to be himself or express himself, both in the moment and in life. Likewise, the story is broken into pieces that end abruptly as the character makes a dramatic realization about himself. This leaves us wanting. There is much of this story that goes untold, which is frustrating but necessary. The end seems abrupt when the credits roll, but the more I think back on it, the more that ending seems like the only appropriate ending.
I only had a vague idea of what Moonlight was about, so I might have to watch it again to feel the full impact that others have described.  I will say the performances were exceptional, especially the young and teen version of Chiron.  There are two exceptional scenes that will probably ring the Oscar bell and a twenty minute dance of empathy that ends the film that was very, very powerful.  This is a movie about becoming a man and discovering your own truth, but then its about a dozen other things as well, none of which overwhelm the central story and that's a credit to the director, screenwriter and the actors and all the technicians who made one of the best movies of 2016.
