Moonlight is sure to strike a chord with anyone who has ever struggled with their identity, or succumbed to peer pressure and backstreet politics.
Charting one man's impenetrable loneliness through childhood, adulthood and in-between, this highly personal film invites us to share central character Chiron's pain and confusion.
Barry Jenkins' tender yet intrusive approach to direction echoes the kind of taut social realism once perfected by the Italians, and the whole thing screams authenticity in terms of tone, character, dialogue and devastation. Graced by immaculate performances and a restrained romance guaranteed to break hearts, Moonlight is living proof that there is beauty to be found in hopelessness - or is there?
