Ok, this was a GREAT movie. I'd like to start by saying that the acting was phenomenal, with great praise for Mahershala Ali and Naomi Harris. This is a movie about a kid, Shiron, who is raised in the suburbs of Miami, and continuously abused and harassed by other kids because he is gay. Because of this, he maintains a low profile and is very shy. He is very strong through  this never-ending ordeal, even with the fact that his mother is a drug addict and abuses him verbally as well, which Naomi Harris does a FANTASTIC job as. So what happens is the kid is "rescued" and "adopted" by Mahershala Ali's character, who helps him understand his sexuality until he dies. What I have a problem with is that Mahershala Ali won an Oscar for this performance. His performance was nothing NEAR Oscar worthy. He was only in a third of the movie, only appearing
Moonlight is a movie with a lot to say, and at times maybe too much about many topics.  Poverty, race, sexual preference, bullying, drugs, parenting and friendship are many of the topics covered in this well made film.  I liked this one, even though the pace of it was a little too deliberate for me.  Don't get me wrong, it is a very good film, but I think it is trying to say too much about too many things at times.  So therefore, there are some items or relationships to me that go unresolved in the film.  However, maybe that is the purpose, and that sometimes in life we don't get to wrap up everything with a nice pretty bow.  What this movie is good at showing are the relationships the main character has throughout his life, and how they shape him both good and bad.  It also shows how many of us tend to live our life trying to be what we think others want us to be or act, and not ourselves.  That is certainly something this film gets right.  There are some excellent performances here, as the little known cast is very good.  The director does an excellent job of telling this story with some really good camera angles and perspective that we just don't see all the time.  This isn't my favorite picture of the year, but I can see why it will be up for Best Picture come Oscar time.
