This is the best film I have seen since "Birdman", though I suppose "Brand New Testament" would be close behind.  It is as perfect as a movie gets- the cinematography and its moving camera drips with emotion without a word being spoken, the script is as tight as that of the drum taut (hah!) "Whiplash", and the story is something you have never seen before and that few of us ever really think about.  So much emotional realism drips off the screen with such sparse dialogue, that it feels surreal in the very best way to sit through.  Although a film about loneliness and alienation, it is inherently uplifting.  Great performances from both children and men, performances that rely on long, uncomfortable silences and facial expression, very difficult to pull off.  Amazing from first shot to last, and after seeing most of the other Oscar contenders, I have to believe that this is our best picture.  One of the very best in a decade, an absolute home run.
Moonlight is a film which goes a long way both artistically and socially, The contrast between the three chapters really highlights the pain and the struggle and that's exactly what Barry was going for, What sticks out the most is the intense and raw plot which sometimes fell flat due to lack of details but as an overall story it was solid, The best thing that Moonlight has to offer was the acting, Pain is not an easy emotion to showcase but all three actors who played "Chiron" preformed wonderfully, The camera work on the other hand is spectacular and a joy to watch
