"This above all: to thine own self be true." That pretty much sums up the movie.  I suppose that I'm not as rapturous as most of the critics--nothing so new about all the "In da Hood" stuff. However, I doubt that I will see better acting this year. The adult Chiron/Black had me absolutely transfixed. He and the child were amazing.
Barry Jenkins' second feature is a truly terrific human story of the power of love, the life of Chiron first off showing him as a nine year old elementary school pupil, to freshman year of high school finally a full-grown coping life of what it's like to be black, poor and gay. Based Tarell Alvin McCraney's high school project play In Moonlight Black Boys Look Blue, Moonlight is a beautiful black-cinema masterpiece filled with a lot of tension, brimming with vibrant colour, a lot of love, hate and depression. Filled with phenomenal Oscar-worthy performances. 5/5 truly excellent.
Based on the talk surrounding it, as I walked into MOONLIGHT I was prepared for it to be another BOYHOOD situation, a critical darling hyped up beyond all reason and recognition.  Thankfully, MOONLIGHT is an actual good film with many affecting moments... even as it's also quite flawed structurally.  The movie's strongest element is the acting, which is terrific across the board; Mahershala Ali makes an indelible and authentic impression with relatively little screentime, while the trio tasked with portraying the protagonist - Alex Hibbert, Ashton Sanders, and Trevante Rhodes - do some remarkably subtle things which illuminate the different facets of the character they're playing.  The filmmaking from director Barry Jenkins is often strong (he absolutely knows how to put together a compelling scene), and he has a definite voice that can be felt coming through.  On the page, the movie is creative and interesting from a structural standpoint, but this is both a strength and weakness.  It absolutely gives the movie a unique narrative spine, however the least effective section is the last one, which doesn't exactly send the audience out of the film on the highest of notes.  The first two sections feel like they're building towards something, but the third section just sort of fizzles out (for me, anyway); where the first two acts are psychologically rich and complex, the third act feels a bit more obvious and conventional.  That's not enough to mar MOONLIGHT as a whole, but it does keep it from being among the very best movies of 2016.
