This is one of those movies that will make you think for months after watching it. Proves that a solid story doesn't need a huge budget. It needs heart.
Homosexuality and masculinity are always subjects for debate. What makes a man? whats considered gay? is it not manly to be in touch with your femimine side? all kinds of questions arise when discussing these topics. Moonlight tackles these things but never before has it been done from the African American perspective. A uniquely crafted film that showcases impressive debuts from not just certain members of the cast but even from director Barry Jenkins himself.
	Chiron is the films main character and we see in three phases of his life, him dealing with his homosexuality. Chrion's life is rough and he learns major life lessons from a drug dealer and his girlfriend, his homie kevin at school and even in the harsh streets of his home in Miami. All of this occurs while he is also dealing with his crackhead mother who seemingly cares more about drugs than her own son.
One cannot sit in their seat and not find this film extremely  fascinating. this is a hood coming of age story and it is done so well by Jenkins. He gives you these real honest looks into the conflicting nature of both masculinity and homosexuality. an overall incredible directing job from barry Jenkins
the script is phenomenal. so many harsh and impactful life lessons are weaved into the story but at the end of the day the biggest element in here is identity knowing who you are and not letting someone determine that for you. The movie actually ends at a good point because by the end you sort of question if he has truly excepted who he is or not
chiron is such an intriguing character. he is an incredibly guarded kid and he speaks so little that when he does speak its like an event like this surreal moment because we don't learn a lot about him in one scene. The layers peal back only when he wants to and that is a testament to the storytelling ability of the 3 actors who played him. 
although I was surprised by the amount of time he is in the movie mahershala ali was superb in here as juan. Juan is a very unusual character and the last person you would think would be able to show promise of being a father figure and yet Ali makes him so believable and plays him so cool that we instantly see him as a good guy despite his immoral background. naomie harris gives an exceptionally compelling performance as this crackhead mama. She goes to deep and dark depths to showcase a woman that is cracking (no pun intended) day by day and is being less like a real mother figure that chiron needs in his life. Janelle Monae in her film debut was actually quite impressive and I really liked what she did with Teresa.
I was surprised by the music it was almost like listening to an actual ghetto opera or symphony. it brough a sense of authenticity to the movie and made for a mesmerizing tone for the movie. Great lighting work and the cinematography was fantastic.
Not much else needs to be said this is another strong contender at the oscars
