Moonlight is the movie we need right now. Depicting a black, gay man's journey throughout various phases of his life, Moonlight is piercingly human and intimate. It features several of the best performances of the year and rings with a genuine sense of the personal. It is a film that means a lot to those who made it and for those who will see it and while it isn't highly original and manages to hit the expected beats of a coming-of-age drama, Moonlight still radiates with authenticity and poetry alike. And Barry Jenkins, an FSU alumni at which I currently attend, directs with a calming, enveloping aura that draws viewers in immediately. It's Moonlight vs La La Land for that coveted Oscar as of now it's difficult to choose which I like more. Both so different, but excellent in their fields. For now, celebration is in order for a film that brings diversity, spotlight and attention to people who are often sidelined in todays cinematic realm. It's heartbreaking an uplifting and understated filmmaking. Rating: 91
