OOPs.guess who forgot to rate it... hach i went to see it with the only friend brave enough to go and see a "drama" ( I remeber distinctively people telling me they don't want to sth depressing)  and i also vividly recall how surprised we were at the movies uplifting and life-affirming message. The story is clear: It is the coming of age tale of a young black kid in a criminal neighbourhood in Miami and how different people and choices influenced him in becoming a person. The beaty about this tale however is, that at the end of the movie, the story is yet not finished and the viewer know, that the person has a new path ahead of him, thanks to a chance encounter with the love of his life whom he thought he had lost along the way . I loved the Idea that your childhood and teenage years may shape who you become, but that you still have the choice in your hand to change your life in poursuit of happiness. It is a true gem of a movie. The story sounds a bit like "Annie" meets "Precious", but the wonderful cinematography and the glorious, mostly classical score elevate the movie to a true paragon of its artform. The screenplay is understated, almost shy, giving the characters room to grow ( and grow gradually on the viewers too), which makes the third part of the movie also the most emotional and rewarding. You meet those characters as kids, you accompany them through joy and hardship, cringe when thy make mistakes and cry in the end when their emotions break loose. The greatness of "Moonlight" lies in the empathy the viewers develop while experiencing the life of a lonely, unsociable and awkward person, whose life goes gradually under your skin, while using dreamlike images and as little words as possible. The movie works like the mind of its protagonist: always esranged with the world, connecting only with few, , using words only when necessary and escaping the cruel reality by retreating (escaping) into his own inward world. 
