Moonlight is certainly a well-made character study and performance piece that thoroughly examines identity, development, and black culture but didn't personally resonate with me and as a result, I was neither invested in the characters or the story at hand. Moonlight will likely appeal to a wide audience who find common ground with the protagonist but the film's simply wasn't my cup of tea.  Feel free to check out the rest of my review at http://filmassessment.blogspot.com/2016/12/moonlight-review.html
It's a strange one, folks. But, it's also beautifully poignant, awkward, and real; an excellent take on how others impact our lives. Being different can be painful, and just like this movie, it can be hard to face at times. 

The three actors portraying the protagonist are perfect for the roles, and they aren't easy roles to play. It is hard to imagine how strange it must be to play such a quiet and moody character, much less have to match two others. The pace is somewhat slow, but consistent, which is hard to do and an interesting aspect of the film. 

While I loved the story, acting, and direction, the score really sold this movie. It is very understated, seemingly innocuous, but it really is the most powerful aspect of this film. I can only hope that it is not overlooked during awards season.
