Insightful, touching and deeply moving, "Moonlight" is a powerful coming-of-age drama that raises issues that are too often ignored in society today.
Moonlight is a tender exploration of sexuality and self-acceptance. A parable of life in underprivileged ghettos of society, told with the upmost delicacy and respect. Whilst Moonlight focuses on the American working class black community, it's moral theme of cyclical self-depreciation and desperation could be retold in any home devoid of love or community lacking hope. Given the subject matter Moonlight could have been an arduously grim experience. However Jenkins crafts Moonlight masterfully, punctuating the bleak storyline with sumptuous cinematography and a juxtaposing classical score. Told through three snapshots of Chiron's coming of age, a uniformly superb cast keep us engaged. Part of the viewers frustration at Chiron is that he misses the glimmers of hope - such as the tender hearted acceptance of Juan and Teresa - and concludes with a touching optimism that his future may lead him down a more satisfying path. Whilst it's far from the stereotypical Oscar winner chock full of barn-storming dramatics and elongated "nomination bait" speeches, Moonlight's subtlety sticks with you. A brave tale told in a bold and unique manner.
Fascinating, complex
"Moonlight" takes a subject that at first seems familiar, but it spins a fresh web around it.  The film brilliantly shows how we are products of our environment and though we change physically over the years we remain that same person at our core. Certainly one of 2016's shining moments.
A whole lot of buildup to absolutely nothing. Competently made, flatly delivered.
Powerful cinematography and character-building throughout. Films displaying the core of human nature, alongisde dual emotions of fear and passion, of this caliber are far and few between.
I'm not sure how Jenkins pulls it off, but he tells the story of two men over three different periods of their life with completely different actors who are certifiably credible throughout. It's not through simple gestures, and certainly not resemblance. I guess it's the heart that runs through our hero's life -- torn asunder between the demands of the street in a rough Miami neighborhood populated by other black men more macho than he is -- and his big secret, that he loves the men more than the ladies. We learn it all in highly polished, gem-like scenes, one following another as we learn the tough lessons of survival, and catch glimpses of hope and maybe another way. I loved this movie, I loved that its singular beauty and soul is being acknowledged. I loved that we can have "gay" movies in which the sexual part is neither hidden nor dominant -- like all of us, it's a very important, but only one aspect of a rich and complicated life that's hard for everybody, especially when you're poor and black.
Like Manchester by the Sea this is a well done movie that is increditably depressing.  I am depressed enough by the election but if you need more to view the world in dark terms indeed go to this movie.
Gritty, compassionate, beautiful, very moving and oh, so existential.
A very powerful film. Subtle moments in life, but each one can tell a story. Moonlight follows a man in three stages in life living in Miami and dealing with his crack head mom Paula (Naomie Harris) and also with realizing that he's gay. As a young boy known as Little (Alex Hibbert) he is befriended by a drug dealer named Juan (Mahershala Ali) who brings Little into his life and treats him fairly and becoming a father figure to him along with his girlfriend Teresa (Janelle Monae). These are easily some of the most powerful scenes early on. Seeing Little and Juan bonding and Juan being a super tough guy breaking down and showing his true side to Little. The second stage is when Little goes by his real name Chiron (Ashton Sanders) in High School. He's picked on for being super poor and called named. His friend Kevin (Jharrel Jerome) seems to be the only person that treats him kindly along with Theresa. This stage is the heaviest because Chiron realizes who he is, but after a series of events runs away from his true self. The last stage is were Chiron goes by the name Black (Trevante Rhodes) now in his mid twenties he is a completely physically transformed man. He's a drug dealer that doesn't show his true self to anyone until one night he gets a call from Kevin (Andre Holland) and decides to drive down to Miami to meet up with his old friend. Fantastic performances here. From the three main leads who represent Chiron during his different stages of life (9, 16 and 26) they all show the evolution of the character and how things have affected him at each level. When he is called Black at this stage where he is a physically imposing person, but still hurting inside it can be a huge talk about how masculinity in men can sometimes be a defense to hide against what they may really be like, or feeling. It's a great film and the one quirk I had was how quick it ends. I wanted to get a little more closure, but still it was a great watch! Give this one a look!
Una historia dura, cruel y tristemente cotidiana. Tiene todo: un buen guion, gran direccion y extraordinarios actores que se desempe√±an de una forma unica. Lastima que el final se queda un tanto corto para la gran historia que se desarrolla a lo largo de la pelicula pero no le quita el valor y el buen trabajo hecho en ella. Los 3 actores que interpretan a Chiron en las 3 etapas de su vida saben transmitir al espectador la tristeza y el dolor que esconde el personaje. De verdad que vale la pena verla
