It has "Sundance Movie" written all over it, which means it has great little moments that are touching and effective, but that's about it. The directing is unfocused and disorienting, servicing the moment rather than the narrative as a whole; the storytelling device is interesting but cuts all tension just when it's becoming truly relevant; and it's hard to ignore how gimmicky some scenes are.
Beautiful in each breath and true in each blow.
Uncomfortable, unnerving, inquisitive.  Particularly interesting in the way the story was told. Casting was pretty remarkable in that they were able to seamlessly tell the story while it always felt like the same person. Let's the audience find the answers on their own while leaving subtle enough clues that the payoff is still worth while. Felt like a lot of subject matter shoehorned in all at once.
There are good poetic moments, but this is one of those films that doesn't bold on me
There are so many good things to say about this film. I can't remember ever seeing a film that has characters so well drawn across multiple actors (the main character is played by 3 different actors for 3 different times of his life). Although I found his (Chiron) lack of communication frustrating at times, I felt it really worked for the film. I also really liked getting to know a life that is so different from my own.
As sophomore efforts are concerned, director Barry Jenkins' 2016 Moonlight is a fine effort of vision, craft and the perfect next step to go into. His first film, the modest Before Sunrise-esque 2008 Medicine for Melancholy, established a unique voice that was not afraid to address topical issues and with Moonlight-a decades spanning glimpse into the life of an African-American growing up from young boy to an adult-is audacious in scope, anchored by good performances (Mahershala Ali stands out) and executed with the utmost of sincerity. With a three-act structure that is somewhat similar to 2013s The Place Beyond The Pines, the outline of the story is unique and adds a theatrical element to an otherwise very human tale about societal norms, being an outcast and becoming the person that one can become. While Jenkins (who wrote the screenplay) and Tarell Alvin McCraney (who conceived of the story) truly create a unique approach to things, sections that fuel the drama have been played out before and parts do dip into melodrama. These things never derail Moonlight but they do hold back the film from becoming something truly special.
-incredible performances across the board.  Particularly moved by Ashton Sanders performance as Chiron during awkward teen years.   So much empathy for him during that time.  Unique story although parallels to 2011's Pariah.  Handled with elegance and subtlety.  Initially wished Black felt that Kevin was "a long lost love" relationship, but upon further thought that would have been hackneyed.  More more powerful that Kevin simply represents the only true moment of affection that Little, Chrion, Black has ever experienced...that he's had to hold back/hide all that he wants to be except for during that one fateful evening on the beach.  3 chapters/acts transitioned well and handled in a way that it was easy to fill in the blanks.
-Was not the life-changing experience that others seem to be having with the film.  Emotional impact was not overwhelming.  Might have liked a little more reflection on Juan's impact on his life although there was that nostalgic moment looking at the beach in the third chapter that harkened back to when Juan taught Little to swim.  Not sure the cinematography is so well done as to merit the recognition it's getting.  The circling camera has been done a million times and felt a little contrived here.
-100% sell on reviews, uniqueness of story, and that it might have a lasting impact on the viewer...WOM should support all of the above.
heart breaking and moving
The most phenomenal movie in years.
I find the whole premise very interesting but I felt not much happened. The movie felt a bit bland to me. However, the acting is really good, especially that of Mahershala Ali. I give this movie 8/10
