"I've been here a long time. Out of Cuba. A lot of black folks are Cuban. You wouldn't know from being here now. I was a wild little shortie, man. Just like you. Running around with no shoes on, the moon was out. This one time, I run by this old... this old lady. I was running, howling. Kinda of a fool, boy. This old lady, she stopped me. She said... [imitates old lady voice] "Running around, fishing in a boat of light. In moonlight, black boys look blue. You're blue. That's what I'm gonna call you: 'Blue'.""
Chiron would ask him afterwards if that's what they called him, 'Blue' to which Juan replied, almost reminiscently, 'no.' It is this small story which builds the foundation of the sound, the color, the feeling, of what young Chiron feels throughout his life.

   Moonlight tells the story of Chiron, a boy growing into manhood in the humid and harsh streets of urban Miami. Those same streets descend on his family leaving Chiron without a father and a drug addicted mother. Chiron nicknamed 'Little' as a child, is left on his own throughout most of the his youth, falling prey to bullies and hiding in abandoned crack homes, until a local drug dealer, Juan, finds hims and decides to take him under his wing, in a way. Juan soon discovers that Little is experiencing feelings and thoughts which elude to the nature of his sexuality, or what could be; Juan enlist the help of his girlfriend Teresa to help give Little a sense of acceptance in a life. In the process, Juan himself deals with a painful reality as his life intertwines with Little's as Little grows into the next phases of his life as a teenager trying to make it through at least one day in high school without being terrorized and into adult hood, where he becomes everything he least expected but society, in a way, accepts as the norm.

   The film speaks volumes as to the culture of a modern society. From the oppression of being anything other than what is accepted to the shedding of his childhood nickname 'Little,' the emergence of Chiron and his sexuality during his teenage years is explored underneath the moonlight. Fueled by continuing bullying for who he is, confusion over whether it's right or wrong, and the anger felt when he is rejected, Chiron grows into his alter ego, Black, crafted behind bars in a cage he put himself in. That same imprisonment was felt for him mentally and emotionally as he would try to forget what he feels is true. There is one scene in particular where Black stares into the street and hears the soft roar of cars going back and forth, sounding close to the soft roar of the ocean sprawling onto the sand, eclipsing all his thoughts into a memory where he felt the most insecure, the most confused, but also the most free. It is a reminder of the way he felt when Juan told his story to him, when he later discovered his true self under the moonlight, and that faithful moment where he builds the courage to accept what is true.

   Moonlight isn't the traditional story you would come to expect from a film, but it is a powerful one that quietly builds on the words that should have been spoken until they are finally said. The performances are heartfelt, and intense, and real in the way that you not only believe but know that this world and the people that inhabit it are just around the corner. Mahershala Ali gives an outstanding performance as Juan, a strong but morally challenged character, giving Juan a sense of duty and redemption in raising Little. Alex Hibbert, Ashton Sanders, and Trevante Rhodes all give life to Chiron through the different stages in his life. Naomie Harris and Janelle Mon√°e give equally strong performances as Chiron's mother and as his mentor in life. The film is also backed but an equally strong and gifted director in Barry Jenkins, crafting elegant shots and building atmospheric tension. Moonlight may be a small, self contained story but it is a heartfelt story and one that is maybe often heard but never seen, especially through the eyes of those who live that reality.
