The hope to make a connection from the heart to the character's plight in a film, is the sole purpose of attending a film; there was no connection here. While there was certainly beauty in the tactful way that Chiron's life was wrought with tragedy, his presence was lackluster. It's surprising to say that throughout all the challenges of this character, Chiron did not reach out to the viewer as much as he could have. There were a few moving scenes, like that of Little's confrontation/realization of Juan's effect on his life and therefore his mother's quality of life. My heart was yearning to keep the wheels spinning in that direction and to build depth of compassion toward Chiron as he progresses toward adulthood. It is a harsh reality, that sometimes there is no plateau or escape from anesthetizing oneself from being dealt a poor hand of cards, however, the paramount merging of the audience and the protagonist's plight was absent. This movie is not about a racial agenda, it is about feeling lost and never quite feeling found. It could have been so much more, it had potential with the artistry of its cinematography and poetic framework; Moonlight needed to grab those watching by the heartstrings through Chiron's eyes and it missed the mark. Overall, it was not a terrible film, it simply needed to synchronize what was churning in Chiron's mine, aching in his bones through dialogue and more outward expression. 
I enjoyed watching this film, but I was left wanting more, feeling empty without truly fighting for peace and acceptance in Chiron's life.
