"Moonlight" is the perfect embodiment of what a "Coming of Age" film should be, but it does it in such a way that it doesn't just attempt to be a genre film, and it doesn't try to push any agenda despite the main character being a black gay man in America. It's just a perfectly told story about a person's life... who also just so happens to be both black and gay. It's used as a detail instead of a plot devise, and because of that it elevates the movie. The cinematography, script, and especially directing is beyond what we see time and time again in film today. The performances never feel forced, the movie is visually beautiful, and this is one of those films that will stand the test of time because of it's subtlety.
