Rare slice of life film
Moonlight is a beautiful character study with some great emotions and outstanding acting.
Chiron, aka "Little", is a slightly-built 9-year-old who lives in a rough neighborhood in Miami. The other boys regularly beat him up because, according to his oft-abusive, crack-smoking mother, he walks in an effeminate manner. "Little" has one friend named Kevin who encourages him to stand up for himself, though I don't think it ever happens. He's befriended by a drug dealer named Juan and Juan's girlfriend Teresa who feed him fried chicken and teach him to swim and try to answer his questions about sexual identity. 

We next see Chiron when he's a skinny 16-year-old who no longer goes by the name "Little". He's still struggling with the idea of being gay and still gets beaten up regularly. His mother is now a full-blown crackhead and Teresa's house still provides a refuge. Kevin is still his only friend but only when no one else is watching. 

In the film's final act, Chiron, who's now about 26, goes by the name "Black", a nickname Kevin gave him when the two were teenagers. "Black" is a big, buff guy who sports a diamond earring and gold grillz and looks nothing like his 16-year-old self. When Kevin calls him out of the blue after no contact in almost ten years, "Black" drives to Miami from his home in Atlanta for a visit. 

it would be easy to categorize "Moonlight" as a gay, black movie, when in fact, it's a very GOOD gay, black movie. But even more so, it's a movie about identity - who we are and how we came to be that person.

It's kind of like "Boyhood" except that Chiron has a way harder life and doesn't become an insufferable twit when he grows up and he's played by three different actors instead of the gimmick of filming one kid over twelve years. So maybe it's really not that much like "Boyhood" except for the fact that they're both coming-of-age stories that show how stuff that happens to us as kids makes us into who we are as adults. 

"Moonlight" is sad and intense and sometimes hard to watch and occasionally even funny. It's probably the best movie I've seen all year, which would have meant more back when I was seeing a movie every week, but still.
