A wonderful little movie, though not without its flaws.

The film tells the story of a gay black man during three stages of his life: Childhood, adolescence, and adulthood.

Let's start with the good. The acting is phenomenal across the board. The two best performances belong to Mahershala Ali and Naomie Harris. Ali is only in the first third of the film, but he brings a fatherly affection hat just jumps off the screen. He's warm, caring, looks out for our main character, Chiron, and seems like he'd be a good dad despite being a drug dealer. Harris is also great as Chiron's drug addicted mother. She appears in all three parts of the film and seizes every moment she is given, ranging from drug withdrawal to saying she loves her son even though he may not love her. A shoutout should also be given to Andre Holland, who plays the adult version of Chiron's best friend in the third half. His performance is right up there with Ali and Harris in this one.

The narrative device the film uses for the most part works, but the first two parts are much stronger than the final third. This is actually the film's only weakness. The issue is Chiron seems to get less interesting by the time part three rolls around. This isn't really the fault of any of the actors playing Chiron. They all do very well with what they're given to work with, but I suppose Andre Holland sums it up best when he says that the Chiron we get is not the one we expected.


Still, the good far outweighs the bad. Ali and Harris should get Supporting Oscar consideration for this and the emotional punches hit their mark. The acting is the film's greatest strength and that alone makes it worth the watch.
Beautifully shot, and well directed. A bit of a slow burn, with an atypical story arc and climax. It did a good job of demonstrating painful realities of the life of this young man without showing too much, or doing so in a sadistic or vouyeristic way. For those who like a lot of action, this movie isn't for you. But if you like seeing the various moments that shape a man into who he is and see how he discovers his identity, moonlight is a wonderful film, representing a rarely seen protagonist.
Barry Jenkins most certainly makes a name for himself. The drama takes its time while maintaining a watchable pace. Feels like a film the indie boom of the '90s forgot to include.
"Moonlight" is a stunning, beautifully shot, beautifully scored, greatly acted film about a young black kid (man) coming to grips with his homosexuality, dealing with school bullies and an abusive, drug fueled mother played brilliantly by Naomi Harris, in fact everyone in Barry Jenkin's newest film are quite astounding in their roles, you could tell that everyone involved in the film cared about what they were doing, and in doing so they've delivered one of the best films of this year, and one of the best films in recent years. "Moonlight" is truly a remarkable piece of cinema and a must see for cinephiles¬†everywhere.
It's subtle performances and methodical placing of just the right dialogue at just the right time combine for a captivating and thoroughly enjoyable experience
I waited a couple days after having seen this in order to give it a proper rating and it most definitely deserves a perfect score. Like Chiron (the main character) himself, this quietly devastating film finds hope in unexpected places. Above all, it truly challenges preconceived notions about masculinity and reminds viewers to look for the beauty in even the bleakest situations. Outstanding film from the acting, the directing, the original score by Nicholas Britell, to everything in between. "Moonlight" shines (no pun intended) by focusing on a more "show, don't tell" approach to filmmaking. You'll understand a lot from its characters and situations in the quiet moments, the music, the expressions... Moving film, really good stuff!
