A coming of age film told through three stages of a boy's life; from childhood to adulthood. Each section is played by a different actor, but what is more impressive is how all three actors maintained the same mannerisms. The main character Chiron tries to find himself in Miami. He grows up in a dysfunctional home, he is a big target for bullies and he lives in an area populated by drugs. He also tries to find himself sexually. It is a story about a young man's struggles to become something. A truly absorbing film that is the alternate, more intense version of Boyhood. 

Grade: A
Inspiring, moving and beautifully made. Makes you glad that cinema still exists.
A gorgeous movie that involves you with its characters and makes you feel like you acquired insight as well.
I feel as if screenwriter / director Barry Jenkins grabbed me by the back of the neck and forced my face toward viewing something that I'd rather look away from. Did the bullied become the bully? I have a rough time watching a child in a rough inescapable situation such as a here in Moonlight, where our protagonist, Chiron, is bullied.  And that feeling is intensified because his home is not a safe space either. Every time Chiron finds a refuge, it is yanked away from him. 

The film is remarkable for its collection of excellent performances. Mahershala Ali (Luke Cage) is so good as a drug dealer, Juan, who is not a 2D stereotype but is a really fleshed out person.  I loved that performance. Naomie Harris as the mom swings from protective to manipulative to redeeming.  Janelle Monae  as a surrogate mother figure is a solid support character.  The movie's first act focuses us in on the interaction of Juan and Chiron played by Alex R. Hibbet. This child actor has solid stares and eye avoidances which lock our eyes on the screen. The second act (high school) buddy Kevin played by Jharrel Jerome appears almost as if out of thin air. The character is so natural and garrulous that we automatically know him, but know nothing about who he is inside. It might be because in his talkativeness he is hiding nothing. It is a remarkable performance for a young actor.  The third act belongs to Trevante Rhodes as a grown buffed up drug dealing Chiron with his own muscle car complete with crown air freshener. He has become Juan.  Alex Holland plays a grown up Kevin.  The characters reconnect after a decade apart. The movie steers us to land somewhere other than the hurt clich√© that I felt was certain to come. 

Jenkins' movie takes it time. It has a lot of silences. There were moments I felt I might fall asleep, but then young Hibbet would do something to grab my attention. Act 1 has a swimming lesson who imagery is clearly one of a baptism, but even after a night to sleep on it, I don't know what Jenkins meant by it. There are scenes that I don't understand how they avoided a cutting room floor (boy fills bathtub with hot water boiled on a stove top). It doesn't really glamorize its milieu.  There are color and scene motifs which bind our 3 time periods and the different actors playing them. I particularly like the head dunked in water as a motif for Chiron. Maybe it is a continuation of the baptism as a theme.

I don't see this as a particularly beautiful movie technically. The emotional punch did not land for me that way it seems to have for most other people reviewing movies. I was probably turning away from the blow. But I have no qualms about praising the performances, which Barry Jenkins evoked to get what he wanted. So I see a SAG award or two in this movies future. I personally am not a sure about the Oscar buzz. 

