The childhood, teen years and young adult life of a gay African American man is told in three segments in this quietly stunning film.  Chiron, also known as "Little" and "Black" at various times, is played by three different actors in the three time periods.  He struggles with awareness of his sexuality, the abuse he receives at school, his mother's drug addiction and erratic behavior, and a general problem with knowing who he can trust and/or look up to (his one father figure is also his mom's drug dealer; he suffers a significant betrayal from his closest friend).  This makes the film sound melodramatic, but it's very quiet and subtle and often feels half dreamed by the main character.  I enjoyed it, but was a tad underwhelmed until the utterly amazing third segment and a stunning final shot.
