Best performances of the year. Beautiful camera work and mise-en-scene. The script was emotive and effective in how it utilizes silence and its economy of dialogue. 
Obviously, its also incredible that an indie film dealing with issues of intersectionality (sexuality, class, gender, race) has come into such prominence. At first it may appear that its reinforcing certain stereotypes (drug addict mother, drug dealing father figure) but the way Jenkins deals with the subject matters is anything but stereotypical or conventional, as the dominant frameworks we're used to seeing in the mainstream hardly ever occupy the gaze of a racialized and marginalized character, like it does here
