I saw "Moonlight" last night. It is a beautiful work of art. The visuals were classic. The soundtrack danced along graciously with the film. The story well written. The acting superb. The humanity heartfelt. The cinematography fluid and purposeful. Wonderful film overall. Movie making at its best.

The story...
A young boy, Chiron, is grappling with understanding his life while dealing with no father, a drug addict mother and abusive children. Along the way, he meets Juan, a drug dealer, who becomes a savior of sorts. Juan and his girlfriend are attentive, compassionate and accepting of Chiron. Their home becomes a safe haven for this young boy to escape the rants of his mom and the school/neighborhood bullies he encounters on a daily basis. As he enters adolescence he is faced with tackling feelings about another boy, his friend Kevin. Kevin invites Chiron to experience some thing with him that makes sense and brings a bit of light to his dull existence. Unfortunately forces around Chiron bare down, suffocating that small spark that has been kindled and his life takes a turn for the worse. As an adult, we discover as a very different character, following the footsteps of Juan into a life that may not be meant for him. As he moves along this path an unexpected opportunity presents it self and this young man can once again see light in his dim routine world.

Warning: This film has an ending that I believe is just right though others may feel leaves them hanging.
