THE TIDE IS HIGH - My Review of MOONLIGHT (4 1/2 Stars)

It's been 8 years since writer/director Barry Jenkins made his feature debut with MEDICINE FOR MELANCHOLY, from which he became an indie darling for a hot second and then disappeared for a long, dry spell.  The fact that he's returned to such high acclaim with the poetic, blazing, emotionally resonant MOONLIGHT gives guys like me, who haven't directed a feature in 4 years, some hope that if you put your guts into something, people just may respond.  

That's exactly what Jenkins has done here, adapting Tarell McCraney's unproduced play, In Moonlight Black Boys Look Blue to glorious effect and giving us one of the best films of the year in the process. The story, told in three parts of one man's life, sounds on paper like your typical coming-of-age drama.  Our hero, Chiron, appears as a young boy, a teenager, and a grown man in his 20s, with each section titled by his nicknames or his real name, 1) Little, 2) Chiron, and 3) Black.  Despite the fact that he's gay, Chiron's journey of discovery isn't so much about coming to terms with his sexuality as much as it's about finding ways to adapt in order to survive.  

In the first section, he's a sullen, quiet kid raised in the poor section of Miami. He's played with quiet command by Alex R. Hibbert who runs from bullies who call him "soft", avoids his negligent, drug-addicted mom (a sensational Naomi Harris of SKYFALL fame), and finds mentors of sorts with the neighborhood drug dealer (Mahershala Ali, so good in HOUSE OF CARDS and showing incredible versatility here) and his girlfriend Teresa (singer Janelle Mon√°e in an impressively assured acting debut).   MOONLIGHT is quiet, contemplative, and languid, filled with slyly observed moments which would not seem out of place in a Terrence Malick film were the emotions much more accessible here.  In fact, I found the tone of this film to be a unique achievement.  Despite similarities to the work of the aforementioned Malick, as well as the work of War Wong Kai, Jenkins finds a rhythm and pace I can only call Jenkinsian.  He gets his own genre!!  It's arty without being pretentious because the characters feel so vivid and true.   

The first part sets the stage for things to come in this young man's life, where a kind of loving support comes from unexpected places and a budding friendship emerges with the gregarious Kevin (Jaden Piner as the child version) that will help and challenge his questions of identity.  One startling scene shows Chiron asking Juan, his drug-dealing mentor, what a faggot is.  Juan's response came as a big surprise, as do the scenes in which their relationship blossoms.  

The second part highlights the incessant bullying Chiron (now played by Ashton Sanders) suffers in high school, culminating in a shocking, gut-wrenching sequence.  Filled with violence and betrayal, it's a galvanizing moment guaranteed to make you sit up and realize you've been mesmerized by the slow pace until now.  His troubles at home intensify as well, with his friendship with Kevin (winningly played as a teen by Jharrel Jerome) running the emotional gamut and leaving you spent by the time this section fades out.  

Finally, the third part gives us adult Chiron, and his transformation is staggering.  With quiet command, echoed beautifully by the younger actors playing the role, Trevante Rhodes, looking like a very buff, even sexier Fifty Cent, savors the gorgeous patience and curiosity as he tracks down a person from his past, played with bottomless charm by Andr√© Holland.  Unlike the prior sections, this part of the movie plays out almost in real time, culminating in a standout restaurant scene in which two old friends seemingly discover each other for the first time.  The film goes out as quietly as it came in, knowing it has something to say, and not in a hurry to impress you.  Because of its intelligence and patience, it bowls you over.  
Major credit must go to cinematographer James Laxton, A Kevin Smith collaborator, who swirls his camera around the characters and feels like he's breathing right with them.  It's a great dance and an astonishing calling card for this talented artist.  Same goes for the score by Nicholas Britell, which delivers one unexpected and meaningful cue after another along with song choices that startle, such as the opening rap number, or give you a lump in your throat, such as a certain jukebox selection.  Also, I was amazed to hear that Naomi Harris shot her part in just three days.  It's Oscar worthy work and I can only imagine the rollercoaster of emotions she must have felt shooting so fast, but this is a performance to remember.  

MOONLIGHT isn't the fastest film or the most articulate.  So much of its power comes from wordless moments or evocative shots.  It's not perfect, but what it shows of the black male experience in America, what it displays in sheer artistry, and how it leaves you feeling like you understand a person beneath the facade they project, is what makes it essential viewing.
This is an astonishing and devastating film.  Beautiful, emotionally-rich, and true but in a subtle way.  I wept.
These stories need to be told to rid the stigma of homophobia in the African American community!!
