One of the most important films of the decade.
Outstanding dramatic film. Mahershala Ali & Naomie Harris are wonderful.
'Moonlight' gives a voice to the voiceless in a film that chronicles the lives of ordinary people in extraordinary ways. Our entry point to the story is young Chiron, who also goes by the name of Little and Black. We meet him as a grade schooler initially and see him evolve over the course of 20 years as he discovers his manhood, his sexuality and, ultimately, his reason for being. Writer-director Barry Jenkins, in his second feature, brings a palatable weight and gravity to the proceedings and gives us a cinematic offering of the highest order. Touching character moments and emotional beats help to transcend this story that, in lesser hands, may have been much more of a middling effort. Jenkins really knows how to compose a shot as his cinematography is graceful and immersive. Chiron is a very relatable character as he is meant to represent all average kids growing up in difficult circumstances. The fact that he is gay and black is not the only remarkable aspect of his livelihood. Marred by a crack-addled mother, he spends the film trying to defy his upbringing and attempts to not succumb to the life that was laid out for him. Altogether, a very grounded and exploratory work that demands attention while making you tear by film's end for sure. It's been favorably compared to Richard Linklater's star-studded 'Boyhood' and for good reason. This is a coming-of-age drama like few that grace our screens and touch our hearts.
A movie that should have been made some time ago!
A masterwork for contemporary American indie cinema, that's universal and grasping in the most subdued way. Divided into three chapters that examine the life of its conflicted main character, Barry Jenkins explores themes such as identity, sexuality, and romance, communicating on them with a less-is-more mentality. Jenkins takes a minimalist approach to Moonlight, and the result is a film with nary a wasted shot, and very idiosyncratic use of music. It's a fully moving experience, that also pulls off the impossible feat of feeling so grounded in realism, while also having the translucent aura of a dream. An excellent acting showcase to, especially as three different actors play the protagonist, and they all seamlessly incorporate his mannerisms into their performance. Certain to be one of the most lingering experiences you'll have at the cinema this year.
Excellent film. Well worth seeing.
'Moonlight' is a truly remarkable piece of cinema. It showcases a wide range of topics including race, drug culture, and sexual exploration in a subtle way not usually employed by "prestige pictures" and as a result feels more potent and fulfilling than anything else released this year.
