Intensely intimate look at one man's  coming of age.  It may lack the epic scope and unique production of Boyhood but it delivers a far tighter and much more emotional experience.
The new movie "Moonlight" is being praised for telling its story from the perspective of a person not often heard from in the movies, namely poor black gay youth.   While I certainly agree to this, and while this also persuaded me to see the movie in the first place, it does something else: "Moonlight," unlike any other movie I can remember seeing, underscores how societal norms of masculinity can interfere with the self-development of any boy growing up realizing he is gay.  The main character is bullied throughout his childhood and adolescence for being gay by both his friends and his family.   It leads him to a path of drugs, crime and self-hate.   He has nightmares and flashbacks throughout the film where he is reminded that because he is who he is, he will likely never enjoy the self-expression so many of us take for granted.   While he does have some role models to assist him, he withdraws from them because of his self-hate.    The reticence of the main character gives the film a poetic mood, filled with long pauses that allow you to reflect with him on his view of the world.   The movie is divided into 3 sections, and though physically not immediately recognizable from the beginning to the end, the character Chiron is familiar to any of us who have struggled with self-discovery.   The movies I would imagine it would be compared to most are "Brokeback Mountain" and "Boyhood," but to equate it solely on the subject matter does injustice to all of these great movies.   "Moonlight" is beautifully directed, with a great score and even better acting.   On the heels of the Academy being criticized for not recognizing black actors of films in recent years, it would be a real travesty to not ackowledge this excellent film.
