73% 7/10

www.spoileralertreviews.co.uk
To the extent that this movie seeks to counteract years of appropriating "black struggle" for financial gain and removing almost all stereotypes and common tropes of that genre where they might appear, this movie appears to have been a success. That should be commended, because it's a difficult thing to do. 

I question if the struggle is worth it. Is this what movies are about? Representing movies with total accuracy? Is there anything sacrificed in doing so? Am I the intended audience? I have to admit that I don't know the answers to these questions. I just know that it was a good movie - with good things and bad things. Here area few -

good: In order to be true to the community and the social realities at play whilst still communicating the conflict clearly to the audience, the movie had to use a diverse set of storytelling techniques to get us there without explicit exposition. This is essentially a love story where love is a threat. The brilliant part of this movie is that it communicates that threat and that pressure to us almost every second of the movie, but still manages to find a way to communicate the main characters attraction to and struggle with his love for the other. It's tricky, and the script pulls this off. 

bad: I'm not sure if a wide angle lens was not in the budget or what but there was an incredible lack of range with focal lengths here. While I get that this was one part stylistic, which I'm fine with, I have a sneaking suspicion that the filmmakers read a little too much critical film theory and decided that the claustrophobic effect of 90% long lens would represent faithfully the claustrophobic effect of being a poor black gay man in liberty city.  It didn't. Sometimes it was used well to get our heart rate up, close up long lens effects can give us a sense of drama because our periphery is limited, we don't know what's around the corner, we can't see what's going to jump out at them. At other times this effect was created when it had no dramatic purpose. This again, was perhaps a socio-political commentary on life in liberty city ("always on edge") but has a negative effect on the overall narrative. 

good: this move is more or less a combination of Antwon Fisher and Brokeback Mountain and succeeds in literally every way that those movies failed. It's a social commentary that doesn't necessarily sacrifice everything just to make a point. In fact, at certain points, the "point" of this movie acts as a focal point for its more frenetic aspects. 

bad: it seemed as tough every character in the movie was stronger than the main character. This is perhaps some critical theory that the film makers missed. This is because the other characters talked and moved. Our character mostly slept, looked down at shoes, ate, sat down. While a lack of dialogue can be considered a character trait, it's not. This may be necessary to make the character believable but you have to communicate character traits in other ways - mostly through action. If the character can't talk then they need to become a pantomime of multi-dimensional emotion. The endless ways in which the character brooded about told us very little, ultimately, after the first 20 minutes. Whenever this character did act or talk - it some of the best parts of the film..
loved this Movie and the cast was wonderful.
Powerful and challenging. Stays with you long after the credits roll.
Incredible performances that highlight the impact of emotional detachment / emotional sublimation on Chiron, a young man growing up in Miami, but the film also explores this with such humanity: How long can we go without true connection (parental, platonic, sexual) before we break? This movie - a movie that won BEST PICTURE for exploring the intersectionality of male blackness & queerness - answers that question on a human scale. This is not a gay black man film; it is a film about all of us. A film about human kindness. A film about love. And we need this film now more than ever.
