"Moonlight" | C | Well-crafted gritty, gay, coming of age story. Slow and somewhat boring. Overrated.
As the poster suggests, "Moonlight" is a neon spotlight on the life and tribulations of a...sorry, if I say anything more about who he is as a character, it will be a spoiler. I'll just say that alternate titles could have been "Gayngster" and "Brokeback Ghetto". Okay, spoiler warning. I'm not hating. It's just that I knew it was about a gay inner city kid. You watch the character of Little/Chiron/Black sponge up the influences of his personage, and, until the last minute of the movie, he never knows who he is or what he wants. Even after watching the film, I still don't quite understand who he is because most of the time he is sulking, sad, dejected, mad, or just serious - without saying much. It is a rough urban landscape he traverses, one that both nurtures him and throttles him. He imitates those around him, and prevails through tribulations. That's great, but when you are showing not telling (through dialogue or narration), the little dialogue there is should be more than just conversational. These aren't simple people - these are complex and savvy individuals with low education. I know that leaving things unsaid can create a space for deeper understanding, and it can be conveyed by attitude and actions. Often it went nowhere, as if all whispers of character development were simply in service of the climax of each act. The characters (with the exception of Mahershala Ali and Janelle Mon√°e) only engage each other at the surface level and only tell each other (and the audience) their plain motivations. I was waiting the whole movie for a moment when a greater theme comes through or when something greater than the characters occurs. Sadly, somewhat simplistically, we just learn that being black and gay is difficult because of poverty, conceptions of masculinity, and drugs. I know, I know, it wasn't made for me, but it was made for me to see another perspective. In that aspect, "Moonlight" succeeds, and I know it is story that needs to be told. I guess I was just hoping for something a little more universally resonant and less silent and pensive.
Wow, one of the best movies I've ever seen.
La dura vita di un ragazzo di periferia viene raccontata in modo esemplare in questo potente film, ricco di emozione e profondit√†. Barry Jenkins stupisce tutti con una regia eccezionale, ricca di inquadrature ben pensate e grande attenzione al particolare. I tre periodi raccontati sfociano in una fine che lascia un grande bagaglio emotivo e tantissimi spunti su cui riflettere. Senza dubbio tra i migliori dell'anno.
There are very few films that have the impact that this film has. The writing, cast, and score create a space to empathize. To no only feel the struggle that so many of us live, but to find ourselves, wherever we can, in it as well. Chiron is someone bigger than himself.
Great script and very well acted.   One of the best films of the year.    The main character is so sad.
Moonlight is a very important and well made film. The performances were top notch. The three actors who played Chiron were really good. Mahershala Ali was great in his role. While he isn't in it a lot, he does stand out. My favorite performance in this film goes to Naomie Harris. She shines in every scene she's in. The film deals with very important themes, like bullying, addiction, and sexuality. I liked the way the film handles these themes. Barry Jenkins directs this film in a very unique way. He sets up some beautiful shots in this film. I think the film was better in its first two acts than its third. While the third act was good, it didn't succeed as much as the other two acts did. Overall, this isn't the perfect film critics are making this out to be. Still, it is beautifully shot and features excellent performances and important themes.
An epic film, full of everything you'd want and everything you'd want (but didn't know it), Moonlight is a movie dedicated to keeping what is so beautiful about cinema alive--the power of a simple yet emotional and enthralling story.
Last night I had the privilege of seeing "Moonlight" in the Arclight Dome. It's an understated beauty of a film with complex characters, just enough dialogue, and incredible acting. The pacing pulls you along through the inner torment of a boy/teenager/young man, trying to survive a rough life in Miami's projects. I was expecting more of a gut wrenching film, but the points of incredible tenderness were more like getting a steaming mug of hot chocolate after coming in from winter storm. It did feel a little bit long, but then again, I'm usually seeing more action-oriented films, so my brain has to be told to slow down and appreciate things, to take it all in.
"Amazingly well-acted and well-photographed, "Moonlight" shines as one of the best movies of 2016. It never strikes a wrong note."
Movie Review: Moonlight
Date Viewed: January 24 2017
Directed By Barry Jenkins
Screenplay By Barry Jenkins, Story By Tarell Alvin McCraney, Based on the play "In Moonlight Black Boys Look Blue" by Tarell Alvin McCraney
Starring: Trevante Rhodes, Ashton Sanders, Alex Hibbert, Jharrel Jerome, Andre Holland, Jaden Piner, Patrick Decile, Mahershala Ali, Naomie Harris and Janelle Monae.

This beautiful and essential movie feels like the work of a great poet. "Moonlight" is a breathlessly stunning achievement from director Barry Jenkins and it also feels socially relevant due to dark times in America right now. "Moonlight" centers around a shy and quietly withdrawn child named Chiron whose story is told in three compelling chapters, i. Little (Childhood), ii. Chiron (Teenhood) and iii. Black (Adulthood).

Amazingly well-acted and well-photographed by cinematographer James Laxton, "Moonlight" shines as one of the best movies of 2016. It never strikes a wrong note. In the first episode "Little", Chiron (Alex Hibbert) is a shy and quietly withdrawn child who gets picked on by a group of bullies and he runs and hides in an empty house. Chiron is later found by a crack dealer named Juan (Mahershala Ali) who takes him into his home where he scores an unlikely friendship with him. Chiron starts to open up and reveals that he has no father to raise him and he lives with her abusive and crack addict mother, Paula (Naomie Harris).

Chiron turns to Juan and his live-in girlfriend, Teresa (Janelle Monae) more as his father/and mother figures and he spends more time with him and he also finds a friend named Kevin (Jaden Piner) who he grows more attached to. In the second chapter "Chiron", we see a teenaged Chiron (Ashton Sanders) who continues to be a close friend of Kevin (Jharrel Jerome) but he gets severely bullied daily by his fellow peer and student, Terrel (Patrick Decile). Even though Juan is now deceased, it doesn't stop Chiron from continuing to visit Teresa and he still often spends nights at her house because her mother is still a crack-addicted mess.

Continuing to be the target of Terrel's relentless bullying, a social worker pressures Chiron to either suspend them or pressing any charges but he doesn't believe any of that is going to stop the bullying so he takes matters into his own hands by smashing a chair into Terrel's back which gets him arrested. Chiron's relationship with Kevin also turns estranged because he and Terrel partook in beating him up in the school yard.

In the third chapter "Black", Chiron (Trevante Rhodes) is now a hardened adult and drug dealer who lives outside Atlanta and he now goes by the name Black. One night, he gets a phone call from Kevin (Andre Holland) who works as a server and cook at a diner and he asks Chiron to come and visit him in Miami. Kevin also apologizes to Chiron for his unthinkable actions in the school yard which drove Chiron to revenge and hit Terrel in the back. Chiron first comes to a drug treatment facility where his drug-addict mother now resides. Chiron despises her previous behavior with him but their tense conversation comes to a pleasing conclusion when he tearfully forgives her.

Chiron finally comes to Miami to visit Kevin and he admits that he's never been in relationship with another person. Kevin was the only person Chiron ever thought about because he's intimately gay. All three actors (Alex Hibbert, Ashton Sanders and Trevante Rhodes) who play Chiron in three different time periods are terrific in habiting this one role and familiar supporting actors Mahershala Ali and Naomie Harris give extraordinary, Oscar-worthy performances as the crack dealer who cares for little Chiron and the crack-addict mother who ignores and mostly abuses Chiron.

"Moonlight" reminded me a lot of "Boyhood" because it tells another slice-of-life story in America and it's told in three separate dramatic stages. Writer and director Barry Jenkins (Medicine for Melancholy) who adapts from Tarell Alvin McCraney's critically acclaimed play "In Moonlight Black Boys Look Blue" doesn't hold anything back or make a false move. He tackles the difficulties of dealing with loneliness and cultural sexually in a way that's universal and remarkably authentic.

Deeply moving, sad, brilliant and great all around, I cannot recommend it any higher.
Moonlight  is a well crafted drama about a relevant and important subject, the director Barry Jenkins manages to keep emotion in the right place with a strong ensemble cast, impeccable production and an narrative that don't have fear to show how society most of the time fails to deal with serious issues like bullying and sexual orientation. (4,5/5)
It was heavy but good.  Would not be surprised if a best actor or supporting actor nomination came from the Oscar Academy.  Story was a little slow and the ending was a little disappointing.  Overall I enjoyed it.
Moonlight asks the audience for their patience, and its subtle quiet examination of a black gay male's life pays off in ways you won't expect; one of the year's rare feats in cinema
Masterfully directed and acted, Moonlight tells a poignant coming of age story, of a person who grows up in a very harsh environment, that beautifully and intimately highlights the moments, the people and the decisions that shape a person.
Not the cinematic orgasm it's hyped as, but good flick.
Although Barry Jenkins' film is indeed about the struggles and difficulties of a person embracing his culturally reviled sexuality, the story is universal in scope and intent.
A masterpiece. Beautiful, wonderful, heartbreaking, touching...all the words. Reminded me of why I love the movies.
Powerfully acted by all 3 of the leads who play Chiron (the main character) as well as outstanding performances by Mahershala Ali and Naomi Harris, Moonlight is the story of a gay African American boy growing up around Miami with a drug dealer father figure and a drug addict mother. We watch as Chiron goes through 3 key points in his life: a kid growing up and learning what it even means to be gay, a teenager who learns the harsh truths about how society and culture can treat members of the LGBTQ community and lastly as him as an adult finally confronting his homosexuality. From a technical standpoint this movie is brilliant as the cinematography, score, screenplay, and direction are all spot on as well as all of the performances. The story is fantastic although my major gripe with the film is the ending as it just sort of ends with no real conclusion. Chiron finally confronts his demons, theres a scene of catharsis and then it ends...No real climax or resolution. As a piece of film and based on a true life experience the film is fantastic and portrays it's characters beautifully and hauntingly. Overall the film is definitely one of 2016s best with my only gripe being an unfinished ending. That being said I can't argue it's best picture win tonight at the Oscars even after the screw up with the best picture award. Definitely worth seeing though. 4.5/5
Absolutely loved this movie. Its not easy to watch but the performances are superb.Some Oscar nods for sure.
This film is close to perfet. We are immersed in a heartbreaking journey of the main character as he tries to face his true identity while dealing with his culture, mother and social pressures. The acting and cinematography are top notch. It's a story that needs to be told, and it is told in the least preachy way possible. It uses silence, at times, to create the most powerful emotions.
Moonlight is a powerful (I wanted to avoid saying that word, but I can't) and sensitively-made work of art that highlights the day to day existence of a young, intersectional man coming of age. The acting is stellar across the board, the script and camera work have a naturalistic (but occasionally heightened) feel, while the gorgeous lighting (a strange thing to praise, I know) makes the movie's themes feel...immersive. In many ways, I think Moonlight is an effective counterpart to Brokeback Mountain - one of my favorite films ever made - for the modern age.
