I was a little skeptical of the format of "different stages of life," especially since no one can top "Boyhood." But it's not gimmicky and it's not the selling point. It's just a genuine part of the story and more importantly applies well to the setting in this film. The script is nearly flawless and the central three performances of the main character elevate it into exceptional territory. Also, we need more films about diversity like this.
