Moonlight is perhaps the best film i've seen all year. All of the performances, the cinematography, and Barry Jenkins' writing and directing are all excellent. Moonlight never feels repetitive nor boring. It's an exceptionally executed story of a man dealing with the struggles of his everyday life and we see the unfold beautifully. I recommend Moonlight to everyone.
Film language is used as a canvas for one of the most poetic and expressionistic takes on male identity and human relations in recent memory. Jenkins' aesthetic sensibilities and James Laxton's lyrical cinematography create an atmosphere of intimacy that dwell in the landmark experiences in Chiron's life.

This stylistic approach reminiscent of Christopher Doyle's Wong Kar-Wai collaborations is let loose during the first two chapters, while we as spectators are engaged viscerally as the character develops in front of our eyes. In the final chapter, the aesthetic subversion is dialed down a knot, but just because the restraint is then used to emphasise the powerful nature of the situations, elevated by the resonance of what we've seen the character go through so far. This closure is so effective it actually gives new context to the rest of the film, stunning with a circular reflexion as beautiful as it is devastating.

In a Criterion segment, Jenkins raved about Wong's ability to take interiority and translating it to the screen. Well, this might not reach the perfection of In The Mood For Love, but what a way to pay homage to his cinematic hero.
A transcendent experience, not only visually, but emotionally.
Very Wong Kar-wai alike
